Title: Getting started · ArkEnv

URL Source: https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/quickstart

Markdown Content:
ArkEnv is tested on [**Next.js****16.x**](https://github.com/yamcodes/arkenv/tree/main/examples/with-nextjs), [**Node.js LTS** and **Current**](https://github.com/yamcodes/arkenv/tree/main/examples/basic), [**Vite** from **4.x** to **8.x**](https://github.com/yamcodes/arkenv/tree/main/examples/with-vite-react), and [**Bun 1.3.x**](https://github.com/yamcodes/arkenv/tree/main/examples/with-bun). Older versions may work but are not officially supported.

The easiest way to get started is with the [ArkEnv CLI](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/cli). It automatically configures ArkEnv for your project, installs dependencies, and scaffolds your initial schema.

Your `env.ts` file is where the ✨magic✨ happens – variables referenced from this object are guaranteed to match the schema defined here.

```
import , {  } from 'arkenv';

export const  = ({
  // Automatic inference for simple literals
  : "'development' | 'production' | 'test' = 'development'",

  // Database configuration
  : "string.host",
  : "number.port = 5432",

  // Complex types and arrays via ArkType
  : ("string[]").(() => ["localhost"]),

  // Optional environment variable
  "API_KEY?": 'string'
});
```

Environment variables can be loaded [in different ways](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables), but the most common approach is to use a `.env` file at the root of your project:

```
LOG_LEVEL=info
API_KEY=secret
ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000,https://example.com
```

> We recommend [not committing the `.env` file to version control](https://12factor.net/config).

You can now import the **validated**, **typesafe** env object anywhere in your codebase.

```
import {  } from './env';

const  = {
  : .,
  : .,
  : . === 'development'
};

.(`Connecting to ${.}:${.}...`);
```

Title: How to load environment variables · ArkEnv

URL Source: https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables

Markdown Content:
Learn environment variables management in different environments and deployment scenarios.

### [Using `.env` files](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#using-env-files)

The most common way to manage environment variables during development is using `.env` files:

```
DATABASE_HOST=localhost
DATABASE_PORT=5432
NODE_ENV=development
API_KEY=your-secret-key
LOG_LEVEL=debug
```

### [Best practices for `.env` files](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#best-practices-for-env-files)

1.   **Document required variables** Create a `.env.example` file to document required variables:

```
DATABASE_HOST=localhost
DATABASE_PORT=5432
NODE_ENV=development
API_KEY=your-secret-key-here
LOG_LEVEL=info
```
2.   **Gitignore configuration** Add these patterns to your `.gitignore`:

```
.env
.env.*
!.env.example
```
3.   **Environment-specific files** Use different files for different environments:

    *   `.env.development` - Development settings
    *   `.env.test` - Test environment settings
    *   `.env.production` - Production defaults (if needed)

### [Using dotenv](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#using-dotenv)

The simplest way to load environment variables is using the `dotenv` package:

```
import 'dotenv/config';
// or
import * as dotenv from 'dotenv';
dotenv.config();
```

### [Framework-specific solutions](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#framework-specific-solutions)

Many frameworks have built-in support for environment variables:

#### [Next.js](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#nextjs)

*   Automatically loads `.env*` files
*   Supports environment-specific files (`.env.development`, `.env.production`)
*   [Next.js Environment Variables Documentation](https://nextjs.org/docs/basic-features/environment-variables)

#### [Vite](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#vite)

*   Automatically loads `.env` files
*   Supports mode-specific files (`.env.development`, `.env.production`)
*   [Vite Env Variables Documentation](https://vitejs.dev/guide/env-and-mode.html)

#### [Express](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#express)

```
import express from 'express';
import dotenv from 'dotenv';

dotenv.config();
const app = express();
```

#### [Nest.js](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#nestjs)

```
import { ConfigModule } from '@nestjs/config';

@Module({
  imports: [
    ConfigModule.forRoot({
      isGlobal: true,
    }),
  ],
})
```

### [Runtime arguments](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#runtime-arguments)

You can also supply variables when running your application:

`DATABASE_HOST=localhost DATABASE_PORT=5432 npm start`
### [Cloud platforms](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#cloud-platforms)

#### [AWS](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#aws)

*   Use AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store for non-sensitive values
*   Use AWS Secrets Manager for sensitive values
*   Set environment variables in ECS Task Definitions or Lambda configurations

#### [Google cloud platform](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#google-cloud-platform)

*   Use Cloud Secret Manager for sensitive values
*   Set environment variables in Cloud Run or App Engine configurations

#### [Azure](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#azure)

*   Use Azure Key Vault for sensitive values
*   Configure App Settings in Azure App Service

### [Container environments](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#container-environments)

#### [Docker](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#docker)

`ENV NODE_ENV=production`
```
services:
  app:
    environment:
      - NODE_ENV=production
      - DATABASE_HOST=db
```

#### [Kubernetes](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#kubernetes)

```
spec:
  containers:
    - name: app
      env:
        - name: NODE_ENV
          value: "production"
        - name: DATABASE_HOST
          valueFrom:
            configMapKeyRef:
              name: app-config
              key: database-host
```

### [Traditional hosting](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#traditional-hosting)

*   Set environment variables through the hosting platform's dashboard
*   Use deployment scripts to configure environment variables
*   Consider using configuration management tools

1.   **Never commit sensitive values**

    *   Keep `.env` files out of version control
    *   Use secrets management services in production

2.   **Use different values per environment**

    *   Don't share sensitive credentials between environments
    *   Use environment-specific configurations

3.   **Access control**

    *   Limit access to production environment variables
    *   Use role-based access control for secrets management

4.   **Encryption**

    *   Encrypt sensitive values at rest
    *   Use secure channels for transmitting secrets

ArkEnv helps ensure your environment variables are valid:

```
import  from 'arkenv';

export const  = ({
  // Required variables with validation
  : "string.host",
  : "number.port",

  // Boolean values (accepts "true"/"false" strings, converts to boolean)
  : "boolean",

  // Optional variables with defaults
  : "'debug' | 'info' | 'warn' | 'error' = 'info'",

  // Optional variables
  "FEATURE_FLAGS?": 'string[]'
});
```

ArkEnv supports several configuration options to customize its behavior:

### [Entry point](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#entry-point)

Choose between `arkenv` (requires ArkType) or `arkenv/standard` (ArkType-free):

```
import  from 'arkenv';
import  from 'arkenv/standard';
import {  } from 'zod';

// arkenv - requires ArkType to be installed
const  = ({
  : "number.port",
  : "string.host",
});

// arkenv/standard - works without ArkType
const  = ({
  : ..().().(0).(65535),
  : .(),
});
```

### [Coercion](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#coercion)

Control automatic type conversion (not available in `arkenv/standard`):

```
import  from 'arkenv';

// Coercion enabled (default)
const  = ({
  : "number.port", // "3000" becomes 3000
});

// Coercion disabled
const  = (
  {
    : "number.port",
  },
  { : false } // Must be a number; strings (like those from process.env) will fail
);
```

Since `process.env` values are always strings, using `coerce: false` with numeric or boolean schemas will cause validation to fail unless you provide a custom `env` source containing the expected literal types.

### [Custom environment source](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#custom-environment-source)

Provide a custom environment object:

```
import  from 'arkenv';

const  = (
  {
    : "number.port",
  },
  {
    : {
      : "3000",
      // ... other variables
    },
  }
);
```

### [Array format](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#array-format)

Control how arrays are parsed (not available in `arkenv/standard`):

```
import  from 'arkenv';

// Comma-separated (default)
const  = (
  {
    : "string[]",
  },
  {
    : { : "web, app, api" },
    : "comma",
  }
);

// JSON format
const  = (
  {
    : "string[]",
  },
  {
    : { : '["web", "app"]' },
    : "json",
  }
);
```

For more details on configuration options, see the [coercion documentation](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/coercion) and [Standard Schema integration guide](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/integrations/standard-schema).

### [Configuration factory](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#configuration-factory)

Create a configuration factory to handle different environments:

```
import  from 'arkenv';

const  = () => {
  const  = ({
    : "'development' | 'test' | 'production'",
    : "string.host",
    : "number.port",
  });

  return {
    : . === 'production',
    : {
      : .,
      : .,
    }
  };
};

export const  = ();
```

### [Feature flags](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#feature-flags)

Use environment variables for feature flags:

```
import  from 'arkenv';

export const  = ({
  "ENABLE_BETA_FEATURES": 'boolean = false',
  "MAINTENANCE_MODE": 'boolean = false',
  "ALLOWED_ORIGINS": 'string[]'
});
```

### [Common issues](https://arkenv.js.org/docs/arkenv/how-to/load-environment-variables#common-issues)

1.   **Missing variables**

    *   Check if `.env` file exists
    *   Verify variable names match exactly
    *   Ensure variables are loaded before use

2.   **Type errors**

    *   Verify variable types match schema
    *   Check for typos in variable names
    *   Ensure all required variables are provided

3.   **Loading order**

    *   Load environment variables before importing config
    *   Consider using a bootstrap file
    *   Check framework-specific loading behavior

